      "content": "thanks. the baltic states comparison is actually really relevant because the Khovd-Zorig republic was essentially an occupied zone that never formally signed away its sovereignty to the USSR, it just stopped being recognized on official maps. i have these specific treaty excerpts from 1952 that show the sovereignty was vested in the bloodline of the ruling house. if im going to approach an international tribunal, what kind of specific legal framework should i use to argue that the \"erasure\" of the state was a violation of continuous sovereignty? i need more tactical advice on how to frame the succession rights.",
